3 minutes ago, kjub said:

Should I notify him in his thread? Or do you have some contact with him? Or this fresh new smart forum will somehow notify Malah, by itself?

The fact that I mentioned him should've given him a notification.  Of course, if you want to be sure he sees it, you should post on the QuickRevert thread

1 hour ago, nightingale said:

Did some googling - this comes from having an outdated version of Asteroid Day installed - go update that and you should be good.

Asteroid Day? Wow, I didn't even realize I still had that hanging around. Completely forgot about it. Now I just need to find an up to date version of it to download. Thanks for the help.

Under the new forum, we have the ability to add tags topics.  Here's what I'd suggest for contract packs:

Use the contract pack tag as the prefix (that's why it shows up in red), and have a contract configurator tag as well (optional, but ties everything together).  I've also added the career tag, as another broad categorization.

Of course, this is all up to the add-on author, but the more consistent we are, the better it is for the end users.

How do we set a tag as a prefix?

5 minutes ago, Kerbas_ad_astra said:

How do we set a tag as a prefix?

It's in the box that shows up after you type in at least one tag:

Stupid mobile forum software - I clicked cancel not post.

Anyway, what I was going to say is that I will update KSS later (well, now, but at the time it was going to be later).

So I don't have the ability to set tags as prefixes for some reason. May be something that @KasperVld needs to fix (when he gets time)

Edited December 1, 2015 by severedsolo

I'm not sure how Nightingale added that prefix to be honest, it's supposedly disabled. The thing about the prefix system in IPS is that it's much more limited. For example, we can't give you a list of prefixes to use on a forum-by-forum basis.
nightingale is always the troublemaker ;). Cheers Kasper - appreciate you taking time out.

Trying to troubleshoot the scope of this one: some boolean attributes in Contract Configurator parameters are case sensitive.

some attributes when set to False or True are not recognized unless set to false or true, or vice versa.    I think disableOnStateChange is one of them. There are others, but even in the Wiki the documentation is not consistent when expecting a boolean value. Some params have True others have true, some have False, others have false.

I suggest keeping lowercase boolean values across the board. When you get a moment can you double check this? It's made for some very wacky testing experiences.

I can't seem to figure out how to get HasCrew or HasPassengers to not complete prematurely.  The idea in this simple contract is to simply be required to load up passengers, and then unload them all, and not be able to complete the contract until all passengers are unloaded. Once all passengers are unloaded, you can recover your craft to complete the contract.  But currently after EVAing the first passenger in the list and switching back to the craft, the contract thinks all passengers are now unloaded when they are not.

After accepting the contract:

1. Currently you load the craft, load the passengers, and EVA the first passenger in the list.
2. The HasCrewCapacity param prevents the EVA Kerbal from completing the Not check on the HasCrew.
3. When switching back to the craft to unload the next passenger, the Not check completes prematurely. Why?

Any ideas on how to make this work?

This is a simple boolean logic problem.  Take this (trimmed down) parameter from your contract: 

	PARAMETER
	{
		name = HasNotPassengers
		type = Not
		title = Unload all passengers
		disableOnStateChange = false

		PARAMETER
		{
			name = HasCrew
			type = HasCrew
			
			kerbal = @/kerbal1
			kerbal = @/kerbal2
			kerbal = @/kerbal3
		}			
	}

What this works out to is:

!(HasKerbal1 && HasKerbal2 && HasKerbal3)

Apply De Morgan's Law:

!HasKerbal1 || !HasKerbal2 || !HasKerbal3

In short, the Not parameter will complete if any of the kerbals get off the ship.  What you really want is:

!HasKerbal1 && !HasKerbal2 && !HasKerbal3

or:

!(HasKerbal1 || HasKerbal2 || HasKerbal3)

Which in Contract Configurator syntax is: 

    PARAMETER
    {
        name = HasNotPassengers
        type = Not
        title = Unload all passengers
        disableOnStateChange = false

        PARAMETER
        {
            type = Any

            PARAMETER
            {
                name = HasCrew
                type = HasCrew
            
                kerbal = @/kerbal1
            }            

            PARAMETER
            {
                name = HasCrew
                type = HasCrew
            
                kerbal = @/kerbal2
            }            

            PARAMETER
            {
                name = HasCrew
                type = HasCrew
            
                kerbal = @/kerbal3
            }

            ...
        }
    }

This is probably a situation where you want to use hideChildren on your HasNotPassengers parameter - otherwise that nested construct is just going to look confusing to players, whereas "Unload all passengers" describes what they need to do perfectly.

No, as None will actually cause a failure if the child conditions completes.

But I just doubled checked, and you don't need the Any - Not can have multiple child parameters, and will not complete until all child parameters are incomplete.
